1.4 Singapore’s economic revival since 1966 When Dr Goh Keng Swee arrived, a major industry reorganisation commenced to systematically build Singapore’s manufacturing capacity in key industries including electrical machinery, chemicals, metals, shipbuilding and aircraft components.
Technical and vocational education received increased attention whilst at the same time many steps were taken to settle the large number of guest workers entering Singapore.
There was a spate of efforts to turn Singapore into a major hub for high technology industries and to upgrade our to prepare for the highly competitive and knowledge-based economy of the 21st century. Foreign investment in research was encouraged and the mass media heavily promoted the idea of Singapore becoming a global computer city.
Social progress resulting from socio-economic programs, efforts to widen race relations, propelling Singapore to become highly competitive and stable middle-income-state, and creating the optimum conditions for the growth of a strong Singaporean civil society. 1973-1980 After 1973 when Singapore extended registration of employment permits to workers of 120 countries and to political refugees from Vietnam. In 1988, Singapore was fully opened to foreign investment.
